      "content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed global precision/recall regime suffices; harness strictly beats self-consistency only when critic confidence is question-adaptive, allowing the critic to selectively veto wrong-majority sets at high precision while abstaining on right-majority sets, driving effective per-question FPR toward zero.\",\"mechanism\": \"A single global critic veto with fixed precision 0.125 and recall 1.0 flags every candidate set, making filtering a no-op on the already-correct majority. The causal failure is not low recall but lack of discrimination: the critic cannot identify which veto signals are reliable. By replacing the binary veto with a calibrated confidence score p_veto and thresholding at tau, high tau causes the critic to abstain on most right-majority questions (FPR -> 0) while still catching strong-evidence wrong-majority questions. The strict advantage regime is a curve in (base error, precision, recall, k) space: for any base error in (0.5-p, 0.5+p) where p scales with 1/sqrt(k), there exists tau yielding positive expected net-fixed-minus-broke iff the critic's score distribution for wrong-majority sets stochastically dominates that for right-majority sets.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"critic outputs calibrated confidence, not binary veto\", \"thresholded veto policy with tunable tau\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"k = 5\"],\"excludes\": [\"binary veto critic with fixed global precision/recall\", \"critic score distributions for right and wrong majorities are identical\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Critic score distributions for right-majority and wrong-majority sets are indistinguishable (KS test p > 0.05) yet thresholded harness strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Critic score distributions are separable (KS p < 0.05) but no threshold tau yields positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The optimal-threshold harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency but the binary-veto Harness accuracy also exceeds self-consistency by the same margin, contradicting that adaptivity is necessary\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: reuse 44 repository questions plus 60 new questions spanning base error 0.30-0.70; generate k=5 candidates; prompt critic for confidence score 0-1; sweep tau in {0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 0.95}; compute per-tau harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke; run binary-veto harness for comparison. Confirm: (1) at high tau, FPR on right-majority sets < 0.1 while recall on wrong-majority sets > 0.3; (2) exists tau where harness strictly beats SC; (3) binary veto does not match. Token budget: 104 q * 5 cand * 800 tokens + 104 q * 600 critic + 104 q * 5 thresholds * 50 eval + analysis ~= 86k.\"}",
